1. Introduction :
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ        
	This is a GUI Editor for DOS that
was written to make a coding easy	

2. The Interface :
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ        
        The basic components of the interface are :

        Right Click the mouse Anywhere:
        and you get a tool box. 

  ToolBox : allows to draw various available objects
        Click both mouse buttons Anywhere :
        and you get a "Quit the Session" dialog
                Quit : Used to quit the current session

        Right Click anywhere to select a required object

3. Adding 2-Ds :
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ

        Right Click anywhere to get the tool box.

        Click on an object you want to draw eg. Line, Box, Circle ....
        You can also use the shortcut keys. The are the letters beside the
        icons.

        The instruction on the top of the screen guide you through the drawing
        process.
        At anytime, if you get screen garbles, just press 'D'  to refresh.

        2-D objects are just lines and rectangles that cannot react to
        externaluser events. They just add color to your interface.

3. Adding 3-Ds :
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ
        3-Ds can react to external events. You can write the code for
        performing various operations.
        You can also add your own controls and change the appearence
        of the existing controls. Please contact me for more information on
        this.

        Hit '0' to invoke the code editor. The MS-DOS edit opens and you can
        type in code there. Furthur help on this is given in the editor's
        help option. I changed the default help to this. 

        Hit '4' to get the attributes dialog. Here you can change any
        properties of the 3-D object. You can even change the type of
        object ! But be careful, this may introduce a bug.


4. Generating the Code :
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ
        Just press 'W' or use the Toolbox, enter the filename to save the
        code and the your code is generated.
        Then open it to make any modifications and compile it as an ordinary
        C program to get the .exe file.
        Simple isn't it ???

